<subSubSection id="EB9672CF7977FF07FF0EFDC7FD85FC35" pageId="3" pageNumber="14" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A33321447977FF07FF0EFDC7FDFDFCC5" blockId="3.[151,756,621,872]" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="91F8FD567977FF07FF0EFDC7FE93FD2B" bold="true" box="[151,262,622,646]" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: This species is easily separated from the other known members of the genus by virtue of its pale forewings. 
<taxonomicName id="648C5AC77977FF07FE89FD06FD89FD68" authority="Hampson" authorityName="Hampson" box="[272,540,686,711]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Euchromius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delicatalis">
<emphasis id="91F8FD567977FF07FE89FD06FE08FD68" box="[272,413,686,711]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">A. delicatalis</emphasis>
(Hampson)
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="3BB73DC17977FF07FDB5FD07FDF9FD68" box="[556,620,686,709]" captionStart="Figs 1 - 6" captionStartId="1.[151,192,1966,1987]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,257,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[154,1434,257,1924]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs 1 - 6. Adults of Aurotalis spp. (1) A. cristata sp. n., male paratype, Zimbabwe, wingspan 20 mm. (2) A. delicatalis (Hampson), female, RSA, wingspan 26 mm. (3) A. dicksoni sp. n., holotype, wingspan 28 mm. (4) A. nigrisquamalis (Hampson), male, RSA, wingspan 28 mm. (5) A. dionisa Błeszyński, female, Namibia, wingspan 28 mm. (6) A. similis Bassi, male, Zimbabwe, wingspan 28 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/306801/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) and rubbed 
<taxonomicName id="648C5AC77977FF07FF0EFD66FE64FD48" authority="Hampson" authorityName="Hampson" box="[151,497,718,743]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Aurotalis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrisquamalis">
<emphasis id="91F8FD567977FF07FF0EFD66FEF1FD48" box="[151,356,718,743]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">A. nigrisquamalis</emphasis>
(Hampson)
</taxonomicName>
have pale forewings too, but they have smaller females (25 mm versus 30 mm). The female genitalia have an unusual wrinkled extension between the ductus and corpus bursae that is not found in any other species of the genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A33321447977FF07FF0EFC28FD85FC35" blockId="3.[151,756,897,951]" box="[151,528,897,921]" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">
<heading id="F87B96287977FF07FF0EFC28FD85FC35" bold="true" box="[151,528,897,921]" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="3" pageNumber="14" reason="6">
<emphasis id="91F8FD567977FF07FF0EFC28FD9DFC34" bold="true" box="[151,520,897,921]" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">Additions to original description</emphasis>
:
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EB9672CF7977FF07FF0EFC09FAEEFE14" pageId="3" pageNumber="14" type="description">
<paragraph id="A33321447977FF07FF0EFC09FAEEFE14" blockId="3.[151,756,897,951]" lastBlockId="3.[831,1437,258,441]" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">
Female genitalia (
<figureCitation id="3BB73DC17977FF07FECEFC09FE33FC1A" box="[343,422,928,951]" captionStart="Figs 26 - 30" captionStartId="7.[151,192,1996,2017]" captionTargetBox="[191,1408,1019,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,1007,1963]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 26 - 30. Aurotalis spp., genitalia and abdominal segment VIII. (26) A. cristata sp. n., holotype, on the right juxta and phallus. (27) A. cristata sp. n., female paratype, Zimbabwe. (28) A. argyrastis (Hampson), holotype. (29) A. dicksoni sp. n., male paratype, on the right juxta and phallus. (30) A. dicksoni sp. n., sclerotizations of abdominal segment VIII. Scale: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/306820/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
): Papillae anales rather straight margined. Apophyses posteriores as long as apophyses anteriores. Ostium bursae funnel-shaped, membranous. Ductus bursae as long as corpus bursae, moderately sclerotized and distally with large globular and strongly wrinkled extension. Corpus bursae suboval. Ductus seminalis opening in globular extension of ductus bursae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EB9672CF7977FF07FCA6FE7BFB16FE44" box="[831,1155,466,490]" pageId="3" pageNumber="14" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="A33321447977FF07FCA6FE7BFB16FE44" blockId="3.[831,1155,466,490]" box="[831,1155,466,490]" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="91F8FD567977FF07FCA6FE7BFC5FFE47" bold="true" box="[831,970,466,490]" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">Distribution</emphasis>
: Kenya, Nigeria.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EB9672CF7977FF07FCA6FDABFB24FDF5" pageId="3" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A33321447977FF07FCA6FDABFB24FDF5" blockId="3.[831,1436,513,602]" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="91F8FD567977FF07FCA6FDABFC32FDB4" bold="true" box="[831,935,514,537]" pageId="3" pageNumber="14">Remarks</emphasis>
: Males are unknown. The second specimen known is a female from Northern Nigeria, Ropp Hills, 20.VII.1920, and has no abdomen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
